<body>
  <div class="title">STUDENT PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS SYSTEM</div>

  <div class="section">1. AIM</div>
  <p>
    To design and develop a <b>Student Performance Analysis System</b> that automates the management,
    monitoring, and analysis of student academic performance using a secure role-based web application
    for <b>Admin</b>, <b>Professor</b>, and <b>Student</b> users.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>To provide a centralized platform for storing and managing student academic records.</li>
    <li>To help professors add, update, import, and analyze student marks efficiently.</li>
    <li>To allow students to view marks, grades, notifications, and performance analytics transparently.</li>
    <li>To enable the admin to manage users, assign roles, manage branches, and view overall reports.</li>
    <li>To reduce manual effort and improve the accuracy, speed, and accessibility of academic record management.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="section">2. PROBLEM ANALYSIS AND PROJECT PLAN</div>

  <div class="subsection">2.1 Problem Analysis</div>
  <p>
    In many educational institutions, student performance records are still maintained manually through
    registers, spreadsheets, or disconnected software tools. This approach often causes delayed updates,
    calculation errors, duplicate work, poor transparency, and difficulty in generating academic reports.
    Professors spend excessive time entering and revising marks, students do not always receive timely
    information about their performance, and administrators struggle to obtain consolidated branch-wise
    or institution-wide reports.
  </p>
  <p>
    The proposed <b>Student Performance Analysis System</b> solves these issues by integrating authentication,
    academic record management, mark entry, grade computation, analytics, notifications, and reporting
    into one unified system. The project is based on the implemented web application stack of
    <b>Node.js, Express.js, EJS, SQLite, session-based authentication, AJAX updates, PDF/Excel export,
    notification handling, and profile management</b>.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">2.2 Need for the Project</div>
  <ul>
    <li>To replace manual and semi-digital processes with a centralized web-based system.</li>
    <li>To provide secure, role-based access to academic data.</li>
    <li>To reduce paperwork and repetitive administrative effort.</li>
    <li>To improve transparency for students regarding marks and grades.</li>
    <li>To generate useful analytics such as grade distribution, branch performance, and top students.</li>
    <li>To support academic reporting in downloadable formats.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">2.3 Objectives of the Project</div>
  <ul>
    <li>To implement login and authentication for Admin, Professor, and Student users.</li>
    <li>To provide role-based dashboards and restricted access based on permissions.</li>
    <li>To allow professors to add, edit, import, and export marks.</li>
    <li>To enable students to view marks, grades, and performance summaries.</li>
    <li>To enable admins to manage users, branches, and view institutional analytics.</li>
    <li>To maintain academic records in a secure relational database.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">2.4 Project Plan</div>
  <p>The project was planned and executed through the following phases:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><b>Requirement Gathering:</b> Identification of users, academic workflow, system scope, and expected outputs.</li>
    <li><b>System Analysis:</b> Study of current limitations in manual result handling and definition of system modules.</li>
    <li><b>System Design:</b> Preparation of SRS, UML diagrams, database schema, and interface forms.</li>
    <li><b>Implementation:</b> Development of frontend, backend, utilities, and database components.</li>
    <li><b>Testing:</b> Verification of login, role access, marks processing, analytics, notifications, and exports.</li>
    <li><b>Documentation:</b> Preparation of the final project report and lab record document.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="subsection">2.5 Feasibility Study</div>
  <p><b>Technical Feasibility:</b> The project uses open-source and lightweight technologies such as Node.js, Express.js, EJS, SQLite, and supporting packages. These tools are suitable for academic projects and easy to deploy.</p>
  <p><b>Economic Feasibility:</b> The system can be developed without licensed commercial software. The tools and runtime environment are freely available.</p>
  <p><b>Operational Feasibility:</b> The role-based user interface is simple and practical. Users can easily understand their modules and perform required operations.</p>

  <div class="section">3. PROBLEM STATEMENT</div>
  <ol>
    <li>Educational institutions require a reliable system to store, update, and analyze student academic performance records.</li>
    <li>Manual management of marks and reports leads to errors, redundancy, delays, and difficulty in generating meaningful summaries.</li>
    <li>Professors need a secure and easy-to-use mechanism for subject-wise mark entry and performance analysis.</li>
    <li>Students need timely access to their marks, grades, performance statistics, and notifications.</li>
    <li>Administrators need centralized control over users, branches, and institution-level reports.</li>
    <li>A role-based web system is required to automate academic record management and support data-driven decision-making.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="section">4. SOFTWARE REQUIREMENT SPECIFICATION (SRS)</div>

  <div class="subsection">4.0 Introduction</div>
  <p>
    The <b>Student Performance Analysis System</b> is a web-based academic management application that
    supports three major user roles: <b>Admin</b>, <b>Professor</b>, and <b>Student</b>. It automates
    user authentication, subject management, marks entry, grade computation, student analytics, notifications,
    profile management, and report generation.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">4.0.1 Purpose</div>
  <p>
    The purpose of this SRS document is to formally define the functional and non-functional requirements
    of the Student Performance Analysis System and provide a structured foundation for analysis, design,
    implementation, testing, and maintenance.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">4.0.2 Scope</div>
  <ul>
    <li>Secure login and authentication.</li>
    <li>Role-based authorization and separate dashboards.</li>
    <li>Admin management of users, roles, branches, and analytics.</li>
    <li>Professor access to subject-wise student records and marks management.</li>
    <li>Student access to dashboard, marks, grades, notifications, and profile details.</li>
    <li>Bulk marks import through CSV and exports through PDF/Excel.</li>
    <li>Academic analytics such as branch-wise performance, grade distribution, and top students.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">4.0.3 Definitions</div>
  <p><b>Admin:</b> The administrator who manages user accounts, roles, branches, and overall system reports.</p>
  <p><b>Professor:</b> The academic staff member who handles subject-wise marks, views student performance, and updates records.</p>
  <p><b>Student:</b> The end user who views personal academic performance, notifications, and profile details.</p>
  <p><b>System:</b> The complete web application composed of frontend, backend, database, and utility modules.</p>

  <div class="subsection">4.0.4 Technologies Used</div>
  <p><b>Frontend:</b> EJS, HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, AJAX</p>
  <p><b>Backend:</b> Node.js, Express.js</p>
  <p><b>Database:</b> SQLite using better-sqlite3</p>
  <p><b>Supporting Packages:</b> bcryptjs, express-session, connect-flash, connect-sqlite3, uuid, nodemailer, exceljs, pdfkit, express-fileupload, csv-parse, dotenv</p>

  <div class="subsection">4.0.5 Overview</div>
  <p>
    The system integrates authentication, role-based dashboards, subject management, marks entry,
    notifications, profile management, and analytics into a single centralized application. It ensures that
    each user interacts only with the functions appropriate to the assigned role.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">4.1 Overall Description</div>

  <div class="subsection">4.1.1 Product Perspective</div>
  <p>
    The Student Performance Analysis System is a standalone academic web application. It follows a layered
    structure with EJS views for presentation, Express routes and middleware for application logic, and
    SQLite as the persistent data storage mechanism.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">4.1.2 System Functions</div>
  <ul>
    <li>User registration, login, email verification, and password reset.</li>
    <li>Role-based dashboard display for Admin, Professor, and Student.</li>
    <li>User and branch management by admin.</li>
    <li>Subject creation and management.</li>
    <li>Marks entry, update, validation, CSV import, PDF/Excel export.</li>
    <li>Grade computation based on percentage.</li>
    <li>Student performance dashboard and notifications.</li>
    <li>Profile management with photo upload and password change.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">4.1.3 User Characteristics</div>
  <p><b>Admin:</b> Has authority to manage institutional-level records and reports.</p>
  <p><b>Professor:</b> Needs subject-wise student data, marks handling, and analysis tools.</p>
  <p><b>Student:</b> Requires a simple interface to view personal academic information.</p>

  <div class="subsection">4.1.4 Constraints</div>
  <ul>
    <li>The system requires a browser and application runtime environment.</li>
    <li>Correctness depends on authorized and valid data entry.</li>
    <li>Session-based access requires proper login state.</li>
    <li>SQLite is suitable for academic-scale deployment but not ideal for very large institutions.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">4.1.5 Assumptions</div>
  <ul>
    <li>Each user has a unique account and a valid role assignment.</li>
    <li>Students are mapped to valid branch and semester information.</li>
    <li>Subjects are maintained correctly with valid codes and maximum marks.</li>
    <li>Marks are entered only by authorized academic staff.</li>
    <li>Users follow institutional rules for using the system.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="section page-break">5. UML DIAGRAMS</div>

  <div class="subsection">5.1 Use Case Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Use Case Diagram for Student Performance Analysis System</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The use case diagram represents the interaction between the actors and the major functionalities available in the system.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Admin, Professor, Student, System</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Admin</b> can log in, manage users, assign roles, manage branches, and view analytics.</li>
    <li><b>Professor</b> can log in, open student lists, add/update marks, import CSV data, analyze performance, and export reports.</li>
    <li><b>Student</b> can log in, view dashboard, check marks and grades, receive notifications, and update profile details.</li>
    <li>The <b>System</b> validates credentials, stores academic data, computes grades, and generates reports.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.2 Class Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Class Diagram for Student Performance Analysis System</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The class diagram shows the static structure of the system and relationships among major entities.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> User, Role, Student, Professor, Branch, Subject, Mark, Notification, PasswordReset</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li><b>User</b> stores account information such as name, email, password hash, verification state, and role ID.</li>
    <li><b>Role</b> defines categories such as admin, professor, and student.</li>
    <li><b>Student</b> contains roll number, branch, semester, date of birth, and address.</li>
    <li><b>Professor</b> contains employee ID, department, and designation.</li>
    <li><b>Subject</b> stores subject code, name, type, semester, branch, and maximum marks.</li>
    <li><b>Mark</b> links students and subjects and stores marks obtained.</li>
    <li><b>Notification</b> stores user-specific alerts such as mark update messages.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.3 Sequence Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Sequence Diagram for Marks Entry and Performance View</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The sequence diagram explains the order of messages between users, the interface, server, and database for marks entry and performance display.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Professor, Student, User Interface, Express Server, Database, Grade Utility, Notification Module</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Professor logs in and opens a subject student list.</li>
    <li>Professor submits new or updated marks.</li>
    <li>The server validates and stores the marks in the database.</li>
    <li>Grade logic computes the performance grade.</li>
    <li>The notification module generates an alert for the student.</li>
    <li>Student later logs in and views updated marks, grades, and performance summaries.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.4 Collaboration Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Collaboration Diagram for Academic Record Management</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The collaboration diagram focuses on how system objects interact to accomplish academic record management tasks.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Admin Object, Professor Object, Student Object, Auth Module, Marks Module, Analytics Module, Database</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Admin collaborates with user management and analytics modules.</li>
    <li>Professor collaborates with subject and marks modules.</li>
    <li>Student collaborates with dashboard and notification modules.</li>
    <li>Analytics collaborates with marks and subject data to generate summaries.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.5 State Chart Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> State Chart Diagram for Student Record Lifecycle</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The state chart diagram describes the progression of a student academic record through various result-related states.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Student Record, Marks Process, Grade Status</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Account Created</li>
    <li>Registered in System</li>
    <li>Subjects Assigned</li>
    <li>Marks Pending</li>
    <li>Marks Entered</li>
    <li>Marks Updated</li>
    <li>Grade Computed</li>
    <li>Analytics Generated</li>
    <li>Result Viewed</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.6 Activity Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Activity Diagram for System Workflow</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The activity diagram represents the flow from login to role-based operations and output generation.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Login Process, Role Validation, Admin Activities, Professor Activities, Student Activities</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>User opens login page and enters credentials.</li>
    <li>The system validates the credentials and identifies the role.</li>
    <li>Admin is redirected to management and analytics tasks.</li>
    <li>Professor is redirected to subjects, students, and marks-related tasks.</li>
    <li>Student is redirected to dashboard, marks, notifications, and profile tasks.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.7 Component Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Component Diagram for Student Performance Analysis System</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The component diagram shows the major software components and their dependencies.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Client Browser, EJS Views, Express Routes, Auth Middleware, Utilities, SQLite Database, Mailer, Export Modules, File Upload Module</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>The browser interacts with EJS-rendered views and forms.</li>
    <li>Express routes process requests for authentication, admin, professor, student, marks, profile, notifications, and subjects.</li>
    <li>Middleware protects routes and enforces user roles.</li>
    <li>Utilities handle grades, notifications, and email sending.</li>
    <li>Export modules generate PDF and Excel reports.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.8 Deployment Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Deployment Diagram for Web-Based Academic System</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The deployment diagram shows the physical arrangement of the system in a runtime environment.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> Client System, Node.js Application Server, SQLite Database File, SMTP Server</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Students, professors, and admins use a browser from client devices.</li>
    <li>The Node.js application server runs the Express web application.</li>
    <li>The SQLite database stores persistent academic and user records.</li>
    <li>The SMTP server is used for verification and password reset mail delivery.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="subsection">5.9 Package Diagram</div>
  <p><b>Title:</b> Package Diagram for System Modules</p>
  <p><b>Diagram Explanation:</b> The package diagram explains the logical organization of source files and templates in the project.</p>
  <p><b>Actors / Components:</b> routes, views, middleware, database, utils, public</p>
  <p><b>Description:</b></p>
  <ul>
    <li><b>routes</b>: auth.js, admin.js, professor.js, student.js, marks.js, subjects.js, profile.js, notifications.js</li>
    <li><b>views</b>: EJS templates for auth, admin, professor, student, subjects, marks, notifications, profile, and partials</li>
    <li><b>middleware</b>: authentication and authorization handling</li>
    <li><b>database</b>: db.js, init.js, schema.sql</li>
    <li><b>utils</b>: grades.js, mailer.js, notify.js</li>
    <li><b>public</b>: CSS design system and uploads</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="section">6. USER INTERFACE (FORMS)</div>

  <div class="subsection">6.1 Login Form (Admin / Professor / Student)</div>
  <p>
    The login form is used to authenticate all three roles in the system. It contains fields for email
    and password along with a forgot password option. After successful authentication, the user is
    redirected to the corresponding dashboard based on role.
  </p>
  <p><b>Major Fields:</b> Email, Password, Login Button, Forgot Password Link</p>

  <div class="subsection">6.2 Add Marks Form</div>
  <p>
    The add marks form is used by professors to enter and update student marks for selected subjects.
    It validates marks against the maximum allowed value for the subject and stores the data securely.
  </p>
  <p><b>Major Fields:</b> Subject, Student Name / Roll Number, Marks Obtained, Save / Update Button</p>

  <div class="subsection">6.3 Student Dashboard</div>
  <p>
    The student dashboard provides a consolidated academic view. It displays subject-wise marks, grades,
    summary statistics, performance insights, and notifications related to mark updates.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">6.4 Admin Panel</div>
  <p>
    The admin panel provides centralized control over the system. It supports user management, branch
    management, analytics display, recent user records, grade distribution view, and top-student reporting.
  </p>

  <div class="section">7. IMPLEMENTATION</div>

  <div class="subsection">7.1 Frontend</div>
  <p>
    The frontend of the project is implemented using <b>EJS</b>, <b>HTML5</b>, <b>CSS3</b>, and
    <b>JavaScript</b>. AJAX is used in parts of the marks workflow for inline updates and dynamic data
    handling. The user interface includes login forms, dashboards, analytics pages, subject and marks forms,
    notifications pages, and profile pages.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">7.2 Backend</div>
  <p>
    The backend is implemented using <b>Node.js</b> and <b>Express.js</b>. The application logic is divided
    into route modules such as <b>auth.js</b>, <b>admin.js</b>, <b>professor.js</b>, <b>student.js</b>,
    <b>marks.js</b>, <b>subjects.js</b>, <b>notifications.js</b>, and <b>profile.js</b>.
    Middleware is used for session-based authentication and role-based access control.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">7.3 Database</div>
  <p>
    The database layer uses <b>SQLite</b> through <b>better-sqlite3</b>. Main tables include users,
    roles, students, professors, branches, subjects, marks, notifications, and password reset tokens.
    The schema provides normalized academic data storage and supports reliable reporting.
  </p>

  <div class="subsection">7.4 Database Tables Used</div>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Table Name</th>
      <th>Purpose</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>users</td>
      <td>Stores basic user account data such as name, email, password hash, verification status, and role.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>roles</td>
      <td>Stores predefined role names like admin, professor, and student.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>students</td>
      <td>Stores student-specific data like roll number, branch, semester, address, and DOB.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>professors</td>
      <td>Stores professor-specific data like employee ID, department, and designation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>branches</td>
      <td>Stores branch and academic department information.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>subjects</td>
      <td>Stores subject code, name, type, semester, branch, and max marks.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>marks</td>
      <td>Stores marks obtained by students for individual subjects.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>notifications</td>
      <td>Stores user notifications such as mark update alerts.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>password_resets</td>
      <td>Stores reset tokens, expiry, and usage state for secure password recovery.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <div class="subsection">7.5 Key Features Implemented</div>
  <ul>
    <li>Password hashing with bcrypt.</li>
    <li>Session-based authentication and role-based route protection.</li>
    <li>Email verification and password recovery.</li>
    <li>Subject management for theory and lab subjects.</li>
    <li>Marks entry, update, CSV import, PDF export, and Excel export.</li>
    <li>Performance analytics including branch performance, top students, and grade distribution.</li>
    <li>In-app notifications for mark changes.</li>
    <li>Profile editing with photo upload and password change.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="section page-break">8. TESTING</div>

  <div class="subsection">8.1 Testing Approach</div>
  <p>
    The system was tested using functional testing and validation testing. Each important feature was
    checked with valid and invalid inputs to ensure correctness, security, and reliable output generation.
  </p>

